==English==
===Etymology===
From Late Latin ''incubus'' < Latin [[incubo]] (nightmare, one who lies down on the sleeper) < [[incubare]] (to lie upon, to hatch) < [[in-]] (on) + [[cubare]] (to lie) < Proto-Indo-European base '''*keu(b)-''' (to bend, to turn).

